    "top_event": "Wire Rope Sling Failure During Lifting Operations",
    "incident_type": "Structural Damage - Crane/Lifting",
    "costs": null,
    "actions_taken": [
      "IP transferred to derrick barge in personnel basket",
      "First aid provided by medic",
      "Medevac helicopter called at 5:45 pm",
      "Motor Vessel Hannah Ray evacuated IP at 9:15 pm",
      "IP received 16 stitches and treatment for C6 vertebrae fracture"
    ],
    "summary": "On August 10, 2023, at approximately 5:15 pm, during decommissioning operations at West Cameron 33 Platform, a 2.5-ton wire rope sling parted while lifting a water abrasive cutter from a 48-inch caisson. The abrasive cutter had hung up in the caisson and was being re-lifted when it hung up again simultaneously with a wave surge. The parted sling struck an Offshore Technical Services employee on the head and neck, causing a forehead laceration requiring 16 stitches and a C6 vertebrae fracture. The incident occurred in 5-7 foot seas with the injured person standing next to the open caisson without fall protection. The JSA did not address dynamic loading from adverse sea conditions or specify the maximum lift weight relative to sling capacity.",
    "recommendations": [],
